accessibility.text: The two key terms used in the evaluation of an argument are valid and sound.
Arguments consist of one or more premises and a conclusion. The conclusion is what you are arguing for; the premises are the (alleged) basis for that conclusion.
an argument is valid when it is impossible for its premises to be true and its conclusion false
The two key terms used in the evaluation of an argument are valid and sound.
Arguments consist of one or more premises and a conclusion. The conclusion is what you are arguing for; the premises are the (alleged) basis for that conclusion.
an argument is valid when it is impossible for its premises to be true and its conclusion false
The two key terms used in the evaluation of an argument are valid and sound.
an argument is sound when it is valid and all of its premises are true

Validity and soundness are the two most fundamental concepts for you to grasp in this course. Let’s illustrate them by considering some example arguments.
